## Bottom line

**For the same clip-space coordinates, this repo does not configure D3D9 to clip more aggressively than D3D11.** There is no engine-side w-clamp or near-plane guard in either path. The practical reason D3D9 looks clean while D3D11 spikes is almost certainly that **D3D11 is feeding broken WVP constants** (CONSULT-27), so only D3D11 actually reaches `clip.w ≈ 0 / negative` — not because gl05 has extra clipping gl11 omitted.

If you forced both APIs to receive identical degenerate clip coordinates, spec-level behavior is similar: both clip the canonical view volume in homogeneous space; D3D11’s guard band can still rasterize huge post-divide coordinates as screen-spanning shards.

---

## (a) Spec-level: near plane, w≤0, guard band

### Homogeneous clipping (both APIs)

Both D3D9 and D3D10/11 require **clip-space clipping before perspective divide** against the canonical D3D view volume:

- `-w ≤ x ≤ w`
- `-w ≤ y ≤ w`
- `0 ≤ z ≤ w` (near at `z = 0`, far at `z = w`)

**MS docs:**
- D3D11 rasterizer / clipping: [Rasterizer Stage — Guard Bands and Clipping](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/direct3d11/d3d10-graphics-programming-guide-rasterizer-stage)
- D3D11 `DepthClipEnable`: [`D3D11_RASTERIZER_DESC`](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/api/d3d11/ns-d3d11-d3d11_rasterizer_desc)

### What happens when `w ≤ 0` or `w ≈ 0`

| Case | Spec behavior | Visual result |
|------|---------------|---------------|
| **`w ≤ 0`** (on/behind eye plane) | Frustum tests are ill-conditioned; mixed-sign triangles should be clipped against the eye plane (`w → 0⁺`). Fully invalid primitives should be discarded. | Usually invisible, not spikes |
| **`w → 0⁺`** (tiny positive) | Passes `0 ≤ z ≤ w`; after divide, `x/w`, `y/w` → ±∞ | **Classic “spike / radial shard”** |
| **`w → 0⁻`** | Similar blow-up after divide if anything survives | Same shard class |

**Guard band does not replace near-plane clipping.** It applies **after** clip-space frustum clipping and viewport mapping: primitives partly outside the viewport but inside the guard band may still be rasterized. A vertex with `w ≈ 0⁺` produces enormous NDC coordinates; if any edge survives clipping, it can land inside D3D11’s guard band and draw as a screen-spanning triangle.

**D3D9 also has a guard band** — reported in `D3DCAPS9.GuardBandLeft/Top/Right/Bottom` and `D3DPMISCCAPS_CLIPTLVERTS` (“device will clip post-transformed vertex primitives”). It is **not** a D3D9-only near-plane clamp.

### D3D9 vs D3D11 clipping controls (spec mapping)

| Concept | D3D9 | D3D11 |
|---------|------|-------|
| Homogeneous frustum clip | Always (hardware) | Always (mandatory pipeline stage) |
| Viewport / screen clip toggle | `D3DRS_CLIPPING` | No equivalent; always on |
| Depth range clip after projection | `D3DRS_ZENABLE` + `D3DRS_ZFUNC` | `DepthClipEnable` + depth-stencil state |
| User clip planes | `D3DRS_CLIPPLANEENABLE` | `SV_ClipDistance` (shader) |
| Guard band | Device caps, driver-internal | Fixed minimum per spec |

**`D3DRS_CLIPPING` is not a w-clamp.** MS documents it as enabling/disabling Direct3D primitive clipping to the viewport — supplementary to the fixed-function/programmable clip volume, not a substitute for near-plane handling of `w ≤ 0`.

**`DepthClipEnable = TRUE` in D3D11** is the analog of D3D9’s depth test enable — it clips **post-projection Z to [0,1]**, not homogeneous `w`.

---

