**No guard-band configuration anywhere in gl11** — API defaults only.

### Side-by-side: state D3D9 sets that D3D11 does not (clipping-relevant)

| State | gl05 | gl11 | Notes |
|-------|------|------|-------|
| `D3DRS_CLIPPING = TRUE` | ✅ install | ❌ no equivalent | D3D11 always clips clip volume; not a “more aggressive” D3D9 mode |
| `D3DRS_CLIPPLANEENABLE = 0` | ✅ | N/A (no user planes) | Same effective behavior |
| `D3DRS_LASTPIXEL = TRUE` | ✅ | N/A | Edge pixel rule only |
| `DepthClipEnable = TRUE` | via `D3DRS_ZENABLE` | ✅ explicit | Equivalent depth clipping |
| Viewport MinZ/MaxZ | 0.0 / 1.0 | 0.0 / 1.0 | **Identical** |
| Scissor default | OFF | OFF | D3D11 falsely reports `supportsScissorRect = false` |
| Guard band | caps queried, never set | never set | Both use driver defaults |

**No smoking-gun render-state divergence** explains “D3D9 clips near-w, D3D11 doesn’t.”

---

## (4) Per-vertex w-clamp or near-plane guard in engine/shaders?

**No — neither path has one.**

Vertex transform is bare WVP multiply:

```15:15:.planning/research/vsh-extract/transform.inc
m4x4 oPos, vPosition, cObjectWorldCameraProjectionMatrix
```

D3D11 fallback VS matches:

```198:198:src/engine/client/application/Direct3d11/src/win32/Direct3d11_VertexShaderData.cpp
		"    o.position = mul(float4(input.position, 1.0f), objectWorldCameraProjectionMatrix);\n"
```

- No `max(w, ε)`, no `clip()` on `w`, no `SV_ClipDistance` in asset VS.
- D3D11 `Direct3d11_HlslRewrite.cpp` adds NaN guards for specular `pow()` (Rule F), not near-plane / w guards.
- D3D11 PS `clip()` is alpha-test only (`Direct3d11_PixelShaderProgramData.cpp`), not w-related.

---

## Guard band and the spike mechanism

For a vertex with **`clip.w ≈ 0⁺`** and moderate `clip.x`:

1. Homogeneous near test `0 ≤ z ≤ w` may pass (barely).
2. Perspective divide: `NDC.x = x/w → ±∞`.
3. If the triangle edge survives frustum clip, coordinates can fall **inside D3D11’s guard band** (which extends well beyond `[-1,1]` in x/y).
4. Rasterizer emits a **long screen-spanning triangle** — the observed radial spike.

D3D9 would do the same **if it received the same clip coordinates**. The guard band is not “D3D11-only”; D3D11’s is just **documented and fixed-minimum**, while D3D9’s is cap-reported per device.

---

## Reconciling with your probes

CONSULT-27 established that for the same object-local vertices, **D3D11 uploads a wrong WVP** → `clip.w ≈ 0 / negative`, while D3D9 gets ~`+cameraDistance`. That means:

- **Identical at draw time:** object-local VB ✅  
- **Not identical at draw time:** clip-space output ❌ (different constant buffers)

So D3D9 likely **never sees** the degenerate `clip.w` on those draws. It looks “bounded/clean” because the transform lands geometry in front of the near plane, not because gl05 clamps w.

The D3D11 spike is therefore **primarily a transform/WVP divergence** (matrix upload / transpose / object-world composition — see `Direct3d11_StateCache.cpp:336–362` vs `Direct3d9.cpp:4034–4038`), with **standard rasterization behavior amplifying** any surviving near-w geometry via perspective divide + guard band.

---

## Direct answer to “does D3D9 clamp/clip this and D3D11 not?”

| Question | Answer |
|----------|--------|
| Does gl05 enable clipping gl11 omits? | **No meaningful difference.** `D3DRS_CLIPPING` has no D3D11 twin; gl11 has `DepthClipEnable=TRUE` matching gl05 Z-test. |
| Does D3D9 w-clamp near-w geometry? | **Not in this repo.** No shader or state does it. |
| Would guard band explain D3D9 clean / D3D11 spike for *identical* clip coords? | **Partially** — guard band allows huge post-divide coords to rasterize as shards in **both** APIs; it doesn’t explain why D3D9 alone looks clean unless clip coords differ. |
| Most likely divergence for this bug | **WVP constants differ between plugins** (CONSULT-27), not clipping state. |

**MS doc anchors for guard band / clipping:** [D3D11 Rasterizer Stage](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/direct3d11/d3d10-graphics-programming-guide-rasterizer-stage), [`D3DRS_CLIPPING`](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/direct3d9/d3drenderstatetype), [`D3D11_RASTERIZER_DESC.DepthClipEnable`](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/api/d3d11/ns-d3d11-d3d11_rasterizer_desc).
